<DOC><DOCNO> AP880531-0062 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 0523EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-31 0507</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0521</SECOND><HEAD>May Goes Out Like A Lion As Snow Falls in West</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Spring snow fell in parts of Montana today as rain showers andthunderstorms dampened much of the nation after spawning floods andtornadoes in New Mexico.   Rain over western Montana turned into snow in higher elevations,and as much as 3 inches of snow was expected to fall above the6,000-foot level. A snow advisory was posted for the mountains ofsouthwest Montana.   Rain showers and thunderstorms fell from the Nebraska Panhandleto the Texas Panhandle and from eastern Wyoming to eastern NewMexico. Showers and thunderstorms also extended from northeast NewYork state to central New England, and over southern Florida.   Heavy thunderstorms Monday triggered flooding near Clovis andPortales, N.M. Advisories warning of local flooding were posted forsoutheast Colorado.   Near Hartman and Holly, Colo., it was estimated that up to 3{inches of rain fell in two hours. More than 3 inches fell in Clovisin six hours overnight.   Tornadoes touched down south of Clovis and southeast of Portaleson Monday evening, but there were no reports of injuries or majordamage.   In addition, Clovis was hit by hail the size of golf balls.Hail, often accompanied by gusty winds, also was reported inHaxtun, Colo.; Bowman, N.D.; near Edgemont, S.D.; at Hill City,S.D.; near Alliance, Neb.; and at Syracuse, Kan.   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from theRockies to the upper Missouri Valley and the Great Plains fromNorth Dakota into western Texas; rain over the northern PacificCoast; showers from northeast New York state to northern NewEngland; and scattered thunderstorms over central and southernFlorida.   Temperatures were expected to reach 90 to 95 degrees fromsouthern New England to the Carolinas, from Georgia to the lowerMississippi Valley, and in the Tennessee Valley, the lower OhioValley, southern Texas and the desert Southwest; the 50s and 60sfrom the Rockies to Nevada, the Pacific Northwest and along thecentral Pacific Coast; the 70s and 80s in the rest of the country.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 33degrees at Butte, Mont., and Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 80degrees at Key West, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 71 fair; Boston 59 foggy; Buffalo 64 partlycloudy; Charleston, S.C. 65 fair; Cincinnati 62 fair; Cleveland 64fair; Detroit 67 fair; Miami 76 cloudy; New York 67 cloudy;Philadelphia 72 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 68 fair; Portland, Maine51 foggy; Washington 71 hazy.   _Central: Bismarck 74 windy; Chicago 69 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth75 partly cloudy; Denver 57 partly cloudy; Des Moines 68 fair;Indianapolis 72 fair; Kansas City 71 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 74partly cloudy; Nashville 65 fair; New Orleans 70 fair; St. Louis 73fair.   _West: Albuquerque 48 fair; Anchorage 52 cloudy; Las Vegas 59fair; Los Angeles 57 fair; Phoenix 70 fair; Salt Lake City 43cloudy; San Diego 59 fair; San Francisco 54 fair; Seattle 51 cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 63 foggy; Toronto 64 fair.</TEXT></DOC>